monitors.description:
This monitor is looking for free job percentage for RBAC TenantPasSyncJobManager in Full Sync.
__________________________________________________________________
The monitor can fire when:

1. Scheduler scheduled extra scopeIds
In that case the load increased and we don't have enough jobs to process that.
Actions:
1.1. Check that it is a case. For that look here for corresponding queue length: https://jarvis-west.dc.ad.msft.net/dashboard/share/A861DCC7.
1.2. If the queue length starts to grow, it is an issues.
1.3. Look to Scheduler TSG for future instruction 

2. One of the activities takes more than expected inside Job Manager process
Actions:
2.1. Check that it is a case. For this look for attached DGrep query for average activity duration of JobManager.DoWorkAsync
2.2. Find the activity which takes too long and investigate why
2.3. If it is a dependency issue (ARM timeouts and so on) apply mitigation: "Increase number of jobs for corresponding Job Manager via hot config" TenantPasSyncJobManagerThreadPoolThreadLimit
NOTE: NOT APPLY IF NOT SURE: the mitigation can make situation to be worse (for example, if it is because of Memory leak)
2.4. If it is our bug, perform action according to the situation.
___________________________________________________________________
Statistics:
50% - because of Scheduler
30% - because of some activity which takes too long because of external dependencies
20% - because of memory leaks

monitors.description:
This monitor is looking for free job percentage for JobManagers in Full Sync.
__________________________________________________________________
The monitor can fire when:

1. Scheduler scheduled extra scopeIds
In that case the load increased and we don't have enough jobs to process that.
Actions:
1.1. Check that it is a case. For that look here for corresponding queue length: https://jarvis-west.dc.ad.msft.net/dashboard/share/A861DCC7.
1.2. If the queue length starts to grow, it is an issues.
1.3. Look to Scheduler TSG for future instruction 

2. One of the activities takes more than expected inside Job Manager process
Actions:
2.1. Check that it is a case. For this look for attached DGrep query for average activity duration of JobManager.DoWorkAsync
2.2. Find the activity which takes too long and investigate why
2.3. If it is a dependency issue (ARM timeouts and so on) apply mitigation: "Increase number of jobs for corresponding Job Manager via hot config"
Some Hot Configs names: DefaultSegmentedFullSyncJobManagerThreadPoolThreadLimit, ProxySegmentedFullSyncJobManagerThreadPoolThreadLimit, NormalizerJobManagerDefaultThreadPoolThreadLimit, 
NormalizerJobManagerProxyThreadPoolThreadLimit, TenantSyncJobManagerThreadPoolThreadLimit, TenantDiscoveryJobManagerThreadPoolThreadLimit (DOUBLE CHECK NAMES BEFORE APPLYING!)
NOTE: NOT APPLY IF NOT SURE: the mitigation can make situation to be worse (for example, if it is because of Memory leak)
2.4. If it is our bug, perform action according to the situation.
___________________________________________________________________
Statistics:
50% - because of Scheduler
30% - because of some activity which takes too long because of external dependencies
20% - because of memory leaks

ArmFailuresByReason and Arm Failures by Resource Type, and RA retry queue

monitors.description:
Free Job Percentage is low for partial sync. Job Queue may be high. 
1. Sanity check that failure rate may be high.
2. Check if: arm call failures have increased, role assignment job failures have increased, or kusto failures have increased.
3. Arm calls -> look at ArmFailuresByReason and Arm Failures by Resource Type from dashboard, if it has increased, it may be the culprit
4. RA -> look at retry queue for RA (retry priority 1) 
5. kusto -> look at Pending Kusto Ingestion Retry Contexts in the System dashboard (enriched)
